00:06:01,359 --> 00:06:05,119
One concept is indeed the concept of sandboxing itself,

142
00:06:05,119 --> 00:06:06,239
which is this idea

143
00:06:06,239 --> 00:06:09,200
that you can sort of ring fence your resources in some way

144
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:10,720
so that they are more secure.

145
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:12,079
For example, saying,

146
00:06:12,079 --> 00:06:15,279
all right, I'm going to allow Claude to change any files,

147
00:06:15,279 --> 00:06:16,480
read them, write them,

148
00:06:16,480 --> 00:06:18,640
do its worst, do whatever it wants,

149
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:21,920
but it needs to be within this particular subdirectory.

150
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:25,200
It can't reach outside the repo that's not permitted.

151
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:27,440
And it can use the network as much as it wants,

152
00:06:27,440 --> 00:06:30,880
as long as it only goes through one of these 10 websites.

153
00:06:31,679 --> 00:06:35,040
That kind of thing adds extra security to the mix.

154
00:06:35,040 --> 00:06:36,559
And obviously what comes with that

155
00:06:36,559 --> 00:06:38,399
is it allows you to be more productive

156
00:06:38,399 --> 00:06:42,640
because you can just have a kind of YOLO level of productivity

157
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:46,000
without needing to take too much of a risk.

158
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,720
So it makes you more willing to be YOLO.

159
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:50,720
I think I mentioned it last week when we were YOLOing

160
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:51,600
that you might want to wait

